    <h2>
        comments</h2>
    <blockquote>
        "Fragility, to Simonis, is an occasion for an expression of strength; fear, of courage.
        Her aim is for the expression of irreducible experience, directed at the viewer
        along entryways not obstructed by theory. Following Artaud's exhortation to 'return
        by way of the theater to an idea of the physical understanding of images'(1), she
        has produced a body of work that plugs right into the nervous system, jangling it
        in ways that are fairly symphonic."</blockquote>
    <div class="autor">
        Nancy Princenthal, New York (catalogue, Solo Exhibition, Grimaldis Gallery, Baltimore,
        Maryland)
        <br />
        (1) Antonin Artaud, "The Theater and its Double", Selected writings, edited and
        introduced by Susan Sontag.</div>
    <blockquote>
        "Nani Simonis is a person who is serious about art. She is so serious about it that
        it is difficult for me to take this seriousness lightly; I, who take everything
        which is not serious, which is dubious and absurd - not just in art - so seriously
        that it is no laughing matter."</blockquote>
    <div class="autor">
        Daniel Spoerri, catalogue Gallery Aedes, Berlin</div>
    <blockquote>
        "The exhibit of Nani Simonis paintings at Grimaldis Gallery features several works
        from her recent series "ANIMA/ANIMAL", in which a human face is invaded by other
        creatures. We may be witness to the metamorphosis of one being into another, to
        a rumination on the possibility of reincarnation, or to the appearance in physical
        form of human qualities associated with other creatures - gentleness, rapacity,
        etc....
        <br />
        Simonis´images are forceful and thought-provoking. At the same time, they aspire
        to a freshness of meaning and expression."</blockquote>
    <div class="autor">
        Art Review by John Dorsey (Sun Art Critic)</div>
    <blockquote>
        ZauberHAFT <br />
        Der Titel gibt Rätsel auf: schwarz der kleine "Zauber" gelb die versalische
        "HAFT". Wirklich "ZauberHAFT" , vielleicht aber auch verzaubert wirkt dieses Buch,
        das jetzt im Stroemfeld Verlag erschienen ist. Eingebunden ist das 280 Seiten fassende
        Quartformat in Farben, die an Flechten erinnert, die sich auf Trümmern ansiedeln
        und auf Ruinen ausgebombter Städte. Wolfskinder und Steinkinder geistern durch solche
        Landschaften, zum Schrecken der zivilisiertern Menschheit, die selbst keinen Stein
        auf dem anderen lässt. - Lapidar, wie in Stein gemeisselt, wie in Gips graviert,
        liest sich ihr autobiographischer Roman. </blockquote>
        <div class="autor">FAZ, 5.2.2003, C. Schülke</div>
